Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["\<\
An Algorithm for the Placement of a Self-Balancing Prehensile Tail on a \
Leaning Mass\
\>", "Title",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992418899646987*^9, 3.99241890259415*^9}, {
  3.992420680749268*^9, 3.9924207250340967`*^9}, {3.992439966659012*^9, 
  3.992439971739094*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3b4ad047-fa97-464f-8aeb-\
cd553dce18cc"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Model V1 - Self-Balancing Tail with Variable Length", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.929354612578005*^9, 3.929354616192994*^9}, {
  3.929355210549653*^9, 3.9293552190879917`*^9}, {3.9918429510719347`*^9, 
  3.991842958992612*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"067356c3-28ca-4144-be02-\
7957e03610f3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Before changing the angle of the tail or adding more joints, we need to \
understand how balance works. In physics, balance is achieved by having a net \
torque of zero in our system. In this case, our system is defined as the \
following: a center of mass for the tail offset by a distance and a center of \
mass for the head offset by a distance and height. The \
tail\[CloseCurlyQuote]s center of mass is the midpoint because it is a normal \
object while the head is a point mass. For all calculations, we will use SI \
units.\n",
